	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_65286451">Maybe this one <i>is</i> bullshit.  Maybe it isn't: immunotherapy has become very successful at actually curing some cancers.  The larger point though is that, even if this discovery doesn't pan out, there are dozens more in the NIH-funded pipeline.  There are bound to be a few winners in there.  Don't believe me? Consider the state of cancer treatment and survivability decades ago, and compare that to today.  Or for HIV.  My kids will never experience chicken pox, because they've been vaccinated.  Millions of COVID deaths were avoided because of mRNA vaccines.  None of these breakthroughs could have been predicted beforehand, and most required decades of support to become viable treatments.  It was speculative, and sometimes research-for-its-own-sake, and wouldn't have been supported by private industry alone.  <br> <br>

Shut down NIH funding and you shut down the ecosystem that produces these discoveries - including the one that might keep <i>you</i> alive when you need it.</div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_65286451">
